# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-rules-football-in-africa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] Kofi Annan, secretary general of the UN has sought to strengthen the partnership between the UN and the African Union for Africa to reach the Millennium Development Goals by 2015.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] He declared that "Africa isn't on schedule to reach the Millennium Development Goals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] But it will be able to reach these goals if the world partnership, promised a long time ago, does come together completely".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] The question of how to represent Africa in the best possible way in the UN Security Council was delayed, following a disagreement among the member countries of the African Union.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] This was referred to a committee composed of 15 countries to assemble in Swaziland from February 2005.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] The mandate of the current chairman, Olusegun Obasanjo, president of Nigeria, was prolonged from July 2005 to January 2006.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] Next summits will be held in Libya in July 2005 and in Sudan in January 2006.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] The summit also touched the situation in Togo and welcomed a delegation, led by Kokou Tozoun, minister of foreign affairs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] A statement was made, inviting "the international community to encourage the Togo authorities to do its utmost to establish a swift and peaceful return of the peace process in the country".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] Omar Bongo Ondimba, present chairman of the Cemac, yielded his chair to Teodoro Obiang Nguema, president of Equatorial Guinea.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] Tandja Mamadou, president of Niger returned to the chair of the UEMOA following the summit of the organisation in Niamey (Niger) on 30 March 2005.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] Different heads of state participated in the summit: Abdoulaye Wade (Senegal), Mathieu Kérékou (Benin), Blaise Compaoré (Burkina Faso), Amadou Toumani Touré (Mali), Henrique Rosa (Guinea-Bissau) and Tandja Mamadou (Niger).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] Togo was represented by Koffi Sama, prime minister, and Côte d'Ivoire by Théodore Mel Eg, minister for regional integration and the African Union.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] In a final communiqué, the UEMOA congratulated itself for "the results on price stability in the Union, following a better provisioning of the food markets" and "welcomed the actions intended to preserve the value of the common currency", the CFA franc.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] During a 6-year period, this agreement envisages broad autonomy for the south of Sudan which will have its own government and an autonomous army.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] At the end of this period, a self-determination referendum will be organized.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] The income resulting from oil will be shared in equal share between the south and north.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] In addition, the government will have 70% of the positions in the central administration against 30% for the southern rebels.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] Lastly, the Sharia (Islamic law) will be into force only in the north of the country, with Muslim majority.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] It will not be applied in the south, having a Christian and animist majority.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] On 10 January, thousands of Sudanese expressed their joy in the streets of Khartoum.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] The National Liberation Council of the Sudan People's Liberation Movement (SPLM) ratified unanimously on 24 January the peace agreement in Rumbek.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] On 5 February 2005, president Gnassingbé Eyadéma died after having led Togo for 38 years.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] According to the constitution, the chairman of the National Assembly should have been acting president until new presidential elections, to be held in 60 days.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] The army however decided to bring to power a son of the late president, Faure Gnassingbé Eyadéma.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] To endorse the decision of the army, the parliament urgently modified the constitution.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] The African Union, the ECOWAS, the UN, the European Union condemned what they called a "coup d'etat" and demanded the re-establishment of the constitutional order.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] In spite of a ban on public demonstrations issued by the government, the principal opposition parties demanded free and pluralist elections and appealed each day for peaceful demonstrations, which gathered several hundreds to a few thousand people.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] These were dispersed by the police, using teargas.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] On 25 February Faure Gnassingbé Eyadéma renounced from the position of president of the Republic, and announced to be standing as a candidate to the presidential elections, to be held on 24 April 2005.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] Abass Bonfoh, vice-president of the National Assembly became acting president.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] The campaign was held in a climate of violence.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] The opposition denounced the conditions in which they had to prepare, and request a postponement of the election.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] Two days before the poll, François Boko, Minister for the Interior of the temporary government, requested the postponement of the scrutiny.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] In a press conference, he denounced "a suicidal electoral process".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] It is marked by much violence, resulting in dozens of deaths.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] The results were proclaimed on 26 April: Faure Gnassingbé, wins the election with 60.22% of the votes, before Emmanuel Bob Akitani with 38.19% and Harry Olympio with 0.55%.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] After the announcement, there was an outbreak of demonstrations in several cities of the country, denouncing the massive fraud.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] Clashes between demonstrators and the police occurred, involving hundreds of victims, died or wounded.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] Thousands of Togolese took refuge in Benin.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] ECOWAS, the European Union and France recognized the victory of Faure Gnassingbé Eyadema and called for the installation of a government of national unity.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] This was rejected by the radical opposition, that requested the cancellation of the elections because of the massive fraud.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2005-in-africa-p01] On 8 June, Edem Kodjo, president of the *Convergence patriotique panafricaine* (CPP, moderate opposition), is appointed Prime Minister.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] was barred from entering due to the age limit.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] In the second round, Boni won the presidency with a majority of 74.29% against Houndbédji.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] won 64.67% of the vote, thus retaining his presidency.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] On November 15, the Independent Electoral Commission (CEI) announced that Kabila had won the vote with 58.05%, while Bemba had received only 41.95% support, and declared Kabila president.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] upheld the election result, stating that Kabila was the winner by "absolute majority".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] Throughout the year, rioting and violence was rampant in many parts of the country.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] Out of the total 120 seats, coalition parties had won a total of 99 seats, compared to the 17 won by the 6 parties of the opposition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] The remaining 4 seats were won by independents.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] No major incidents related to the election were reported.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] was voted in for a second term in office with 54.80%, prevailing over 13 other candidates.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] Confusion over preliminary results led opposition candidates to question the validity of the elections, and official complaints were filed to the constitutional court.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] On December 23, the court ruled that Ravalomanana had indeed won the election.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] Furthermore, some candidates were barred from participating for various reasons.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] The elections were considered to be free and transparent by all observers and political parties.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] narrowly voted to uphold the election result, despite many mentions of irregularities.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] However, a multitude of charges were brought against Besigye in the months leading up to the election, sparking claims of fabrication and widespread protests by Besigye supporters.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2006-in-africa] President of Sudan Omar al-Bashir refuses the deployment of 20,000 *Blue Helmets* in a United Nations peacekeeping force in Darfur in accordance with United Nations Security Council Resolution 1706 adopted on September 1.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The **2008 Australian Football International Cup** was the third time the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition, has been contested.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] It was scheduled for 2008 (as part of the 150th year celebrations of Australian Football), with 16 nations competing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The tournament was hosted by both Melbourne and Warrnambool in Victoria, Australia between 27 August and 6 September, with a single match additionally played in Geelong.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Like previous tournaments, the competition was open to men's teams with strict nationality eligibility rules.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The Grand Final was played between New Zealand and Papua New Guinea.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea were victorious by 8 points with a goal kicked after the siren.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Like the Grand Final in previous years, the match was played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain raiser to the 2008 AFL Second qualifying Final which attracted a crowd of 76,703 spectators.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] However unlike previous tournaments, the final was not televised.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL later indicated that a regional round and semi-finals would be held in Warrnambool.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL indicated that unlike earlier cups, it would likely be split into two divisions, a premier division and development division, with some discussion as to whether the eligibility rules could be loosened for the development division, to enable more countries to participate.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Leagues were given the opportunity to nominate which they would prefer, with eight in each division being an initial target.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Ultimately, this idea was dropped, with the sixteen teams being seeded into four pools.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In December 2007, it was announced that Melbourne and Warrnambool would co-host the two division event, with Melbourne matches to be played mainly in Royal Park North.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Several potential new sides were announced by the AFL, including an Israeli-Palestine combination supported by the Peres Centre for Peace, China and India.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The USA Women's team announced an intention to send a squad to play against Australia and possibly Papua New Guinea.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Additionally Canada and England announced their intentions to send Under 17s squads.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] As a result, there was speculation over an inaugural women's and under 17 divisions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] However the AFL denied these divisions in favour of a senior men's competition only.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In response, and with the Barassi International Australian Football Youth Tournament being cancelled, British and Canadian junior teams had to organise their own tours and matches against Australian schools.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Despite both international teams being in Australia at the same time, they did not play against each other.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The US women's team announced a 2009 tour instead.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL confirmed in July 2008 that sixteen nations will compete.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In addition, there will be friendly matches played between Melbourne-based migrant community teams under the names "Team Africa" and "Team Asia", as well as the Tongan side which was unable to commit to the full tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Also despite a previous appearance, the Spain Bulls will not be competing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The world team was selected based on player performance in the pool rounds only.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/2008-australian-football-international-cup] India, China, the Peace Team and Finland all missed representation in the team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/49th-parallel-cup] The **49th Parallel Cup** (formerly PanAm Cup) is an annual representative Australian rules football match between the United States and Canada first contested in 1999.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/49th-parallel-cup] Since 2007 the women's teams have also contested the cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/49th-parallel-cup] The men's matches are contested between the United States men's team ("The Revolution") and Canada's men's team ("The Northwind") while the women's matches are contested between the United States women's team ("The Freedom") and Canada's women's team ("The Northern Lights").
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/49th-parallel-cup] The cup is historically paused during the Australian Football International Cup year to enable the countries to compete at that tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/49th-parallel-cup] Between 2015 and 2021 the cup went into recess for several reasons, primarily due to the 2017 Australian Football International Cup followed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/afl-asia-cup] The **AFL Asia Cup** is a triennial international tournament in Australian rules football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/afl-asia-cup] It is the biggest international tournament in the sport that is open to all nations in Asia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/afl-asia-cup] It was created as a replacement of the AFL International Cup alongside the AFL Transatlantic Cup and the AFL Pacific Cup after the competition was affected by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/afl-asia-cup] In August 2021, the AFL announced that the IC would return in 2023 to align with its original three-year schedule but did not announce the host.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/afl-asia-cup] On 22 April 2022, the AFL announced it was postponing the International Cup until 2024 citing "significant investment required from the AFL to host the event".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/afl-asia-cup] However, on 24 July 2023, the AFL announced that, in lieu of the International Cup, that it would be sponsoring three regional events in 2024: the Trans-Atlantic Cup, the Asia Cup, and the Pacific Cup to be hosted by an international affiliate.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/afl-asia-cup] The AFL gave no indication as to when the International Cup would be resumed, however indicated that these are the only AFL sanctioned international tournaments since 2017 (effectively nullifying the 2019 and 2022 AFL Europe Championship).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/afl-asia-cup] AFL Canada was announced as host of the Transatlantic Cup to be held at the Humber College Oval at Colonel Samuel Smith Park in Toronto on August 2–11, The Maroochydore Multi Sports Complex on the Sunshine Coast, Queensland was announced as the host of the Pacific Cup on 14–24 November.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/afl-asia-cup] Thanh Long Sports Center in Vietnam would host the Asia Cup at in Ho Chi Minh City from December 6–8 in 2024.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/afl-asia-cup] The AFL announced strict selection criteria, that each player must hold citizenship for the country that they are representing and must have played in from a local competition in that country.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/afl-asia-cup] The 2024 competition was contested by 10 teams in the men's division and 4 teams in the women's division.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Immigration to Australia saw a rise in the number of Africans playing in the Australian Football League, among the first were African-Americans like Tom Banks and South Africans including Aubrey MacKenzie and Damien Cupido.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Kevin Sheedy predicted an African future for the AFL when he recruited Ethiopian Goaner Tutlan in 2004.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] The success of Majak Daw saw a rise in the popularity of AFL among South Sudanese migrants which have attracted the attention of AFL recruiters in search for the combination of height and athleticism.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] An increasing number of players descended from the Indigenous peoples of Africa have played professionally in the Australian Football League, holding African Australian identity.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Tall Sudanese players are now sought by AFL recruiters to fill key positions including the ruck.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] The government of Botswana approached the AFL in 2009 with a view to extending the FootyWILD program from South Africa across the border into Botswana.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Australian football in South Africa began in the North West Province, an area bordering Botswana and with numerous cultural, linguistic and historical ties to the neighboring country.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] While the sport hasn't been played in Ethiopia, the country is notable for producing AFL players from the migrant community in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Australian rules football was played by the ANZACs in Egypt during World War I.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] The sport has since been revived by Australian expats, with an Auskick program being started in Cairo.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] The Australian Embassy in Cairo has backed the program.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Australian football was played on a non-organised level in Ghana in 2007, where traveling Australians played with children.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] In early 2009, AFL club the Western Bulldogs announced that they were in talks with Azumah Nelson regarding the introduction of Australian rules football at the Azumah Nelson Foundation (AZNEF) Sports Academy.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Nelson was quoted as saying "Once we become familiar with handling the oval shaped ball, I am sure that Ghana will produce many champions for the AFL Clubs in Australia" The Bulldogs also stated that they may travel to Ghana to visit the AZNEF Sports Academy in future.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] There have been efforts to start the sport at junior level since 2004.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Gus Horsey from the Baltimore Washington Eagles from the United States Australian Football League visited the country in February and September, running several footy clinics and organising a grand final between four local teams in Nairobi.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] During Horsey's second visit to Kenya to coach Australian rules, he regularly trained over 100 children after school with help from local soccer coaches, although plans through USFooty Kids to continue the clinics in the future did not go ahead.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] The AFL reported in 2009 that junior clinics were being conducted in Kenya under the same model as FootyWILD in South Africa.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] In 2015, schoolboys international matches were held on the Kenya-Tanzania border.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Educaring Africa ran clinics Ntakataka Village in Monkey Bay in 2019.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] While the sport hasn't been played in Nigeria, some AFL players from the migrant community in Australia have strong connections to the country.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Australian rules football was played sporadically in Senegal during the 1990s, after Darwin-based Mark Moretti visited Dakar for two months in 1991.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Moretti had introduced the sport to local children originally as an example of overseas culture, but there was interest from both the children and some local soccer administrators in continuing the sport.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] When Moretti returned in 1997 there had not been any progress, so he organised some footballs and other material to be sent to Senegal and the country was represented at the International Australian Football Council AGM in Darwin in 1999.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Around this time, two teams were established, named the Crocodiles and the Hares, but the sport has since disappeared in the country.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] A team representing Senegal appeared at the "World 9s" in Catalonia in 2008, consisting of Senegalese nationals resident in Spain and competing in the Catalan AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Collingwood FC recruited 202cm Senegalese basketballer Bassirou Faye as an international rookie in 2021.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] The Witwatersrand Gold Rush brought miners from Australia to South Africa and records indicate that it was played from the 1880s to 1909 and was for a time during 1904, the most popular football code in the colony.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] It was reintroduced by the Australian Defence Force in 1997 and in the 2000s became one of the fastest growing places for the sport outside of Australia, becoming widely played in the North West Province with tens of thousands of players.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Prominent South African born AFL players include Damian Cupido and Jason Johannisen.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] While the sport hasn't been played in Sudan, the country is notable for producing AFL players from the migrant community in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] While the sport hasn't been played in South Sudan, the country is notable for producing many AFL players from the migrant community in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] A team representing South Sudan has won the World 9s twice most recently in 2021.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Non-organised Australian football at junior level featuring locals has been played in Uganda in 2006.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Australian football was played on an informal basis in Western Sahara in 2008.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] In 2020, AFL Zimbabwe was formed as the governing body for the sport in Zimbabwe.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] The successful career of Majak Daw in the AFL is credited as having inspired many children from the South Sudanese migrant community in Australia to take up the sport.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] A team known as *Team Africa*, drawn from various Melbourne African communities, competed in the 2008 Australian Football International Cup's Multicultural Challenge, playing matches against South Africa, Tonga and an Asian community side dubbed *Team Asia*.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-africa/australian-rules-football-in-africa] Team Africa's players were from countries including Somalia, Egypt, Ethiopia, Sudan, Nigeria, Kenya, South Africa, Zimbabwe and Djibouti.
